^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Let's count Margaret's Bergen points. One thing that is not obvious, but what she should do on this hand is count "declarer" points rather than "dummy" points. You should count "declarer" points if you are the hand with longer trump. Normally whoever bids a suit first has the longer suit and that is why Marty calls them "declarer" points. But occasionally, the partner of whoever mentions the suit first has the longer suit.|
PG| ***** 15 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|As part of Bergen hand evaluation, once you find a fit, one person counts declarer points and the other person counts dummy points. There are slightly different addons to your Bergen Starting points. In particular, dummy adds for shortness only. |
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Dummy adds 1 point for each doubleton, 2 points for a singleton with 3-card support or 3 points for a singleton with 4+ card support. And for a void adds the number of trump as extra points. So if dummy had 3-card support they would add 3 if they had a void. The reason dummy adds for shortness is the assumption is that the short suit will generate extra trump tricks.|
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|One important concept that many people don't realize is that, when the short hand trumps, that generates extra trump tricks. But when the long hand trumps, it does not generate extra trump tricks. For example, take a look at this hand. We have 5 diamond tricks based on North's length. However, assume my hand was slightly different and I had a doubleton heart. If I could trump a heart in my hand, that would generate a 6th diamond trick.|
PG| ***** 18 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|However, trumping spades or clubs in the North hand does not generate any more than the 5 trump tricks North started with. That is why shortness in the hand with short trump is more valuable; it generates extra tricks. Shortness in the long hand also has some value in that it prevents the defense from taking extra tricks. |
pg| ***** 19 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|For example, we can only take 2 club tricks since North has a doubleton. Shortness does have some value, but it does not generate extra trick, just provides a means to prevent the defense from scoring tricks.|
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Declarer points are a bit more complicated. A better but more awkward name for "declarer" points, would be "player with the longer trump" points. And for "dummy" points it would similarly be "player with the shorter trump" points. |
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The most common time when the player who will be dummy counts "declarer" points is in transfer auctions when partner opens 1NT. In that case, responder, with a 5-card major, always has the longer trump, but because they are doing a transfer, end up being dummy.|
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


